<DOC><DOCNO> AP890307-0062 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-03-07-89 1106EST</FILEID><FIRST>r a PM-BRF--Judge-Bribery     03-07 0177</FIRST><SECOND>PM-BRF--Judge-Bribery,0181</SECOND><HEAD>Judge Pleads Guilty To Bribery</HEAD><DATELINE>DETROIT (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   One of three city judges charged after a federalbribery investigation pleaded guilty today in a deal that set hermaximum sentence at five years in prison, court officials said.   Recorder's Judge Evelyn Cooper was to have gone on trial today inU.S. District Court on charges of accepting $9,000 in bribes to fixtwo criminal cases and arrange for a convict's early release. Theindictment also charged her with failing to report income from thebribes.   Cooper, 47, pleaded guilty to one count of extortion of $5,000and to signing a false tax return for 1984, said a court spokeswomanwho would not give her name.   Cooper had faced 20 years in prison if convicted of bribery, andthree years for filing a false tax return. No sentencing date wasset.   In the other bribery cases, a state district judge is serving a10-year sentence and another judge was acquitted last week of fourbribery charges but a mistrial was declared on a racketeering charge.</TEXT></DOC>